<portion>
    <section1 id="sAdvP">
        <secTitle>Adverbs and Adverb Phrases</secTitle>
        <p>
            <content>Adverbs express four basic types of information:</content>
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <content> time,</content>
            </li>
            <li>
                <content> location,</content>
            </li>
            <li>
                <content>manner, and</content>
            </li>
            <li>
                <content>reason or purpose.</content>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            <content>These types have different characteristics as to
which positions they may occupy and how they may be modified.  Each type will be covered in turn.
</content>
        </p>
        <p>
            <content>Languages normally have degree words which can modify at least some types of adverbs.  </content>
            <langName/>
            <content/>
            <case element="advp" attr="degree">
                <caseText value="no"> does not have any such degree words, however.</caseText>
                <caseText value="yes"> has such degree words.</caseText>
            </case>
            <content/>
            <text show="swAdvPDegreeYes">
                <content> These degree words occur </content>
                <case element="advp" attr="degreePos">
                    <caseText value="before">before</caseText>
                    <caseText value="after">after</caseText>
                    <caseText value="either">on either side (but not both sides) of</caseText>
                    <caseText value="eitherOrBoth">on either side or on both sides of</caseText>
                    <caseText value="beforeOrBoth">before or on both sides of</caseText>
                    <caseText value="afterOrBoth">after or on both sides of</caseText>
                    <caseText value="both">on both sides of</caseText>
                    <caseText value="unknown">_______</caseText>
                </case>
                <content> the adverb.  </content>
                <case element="advp" attr="degreeSet">
                    <caseText value="unrestricted">The degree words can modify any type of adverb.</caseText>
                    <caseText value="exceptReason">The degree words can modify temporals, locatives, and manner adverbs, but reason or purpose adverbs are not modified.</caseText>
                    <caseText value="restricted">There are distinct sets of the degree words which can modify each type of adverb.</caseText>
                </case>
                <content/>
            </text>
            <content/>
        </p>
        <section2 id="sAdvPTemporal">
            <secTitle>Temporal Adverbs</secTitle>
            <p>
                <content>Temporal adverbs include the English words: </content>
                <langData>already</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>then</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>soon</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>now</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>later</langData>
                <content>, and </content>
                <langData>always</langData>
                <content>.  Examples including degree word modifiers are: </content>
                <langData>very soon</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>much later</langData>
                <content> and </content>
                <langData>only now</langData>
                <content>.  Many languages also have a negative temporal adverb meaning 'no when', such as </content>
                <langData>never</langData>
                <content> in English.</content>
            </p>
            <p>
                <content>Examples of </content>
                <langName/>
                <content> positive temporal adverbs and any degree words which can modify them include:
</content>
            </p>
            <example>
                <interlinear exampleLoc="advp/temporalExample"/>
            </example>
            <p show="swAdvPNegTemporalTypeAffix">
                <content>In </content>
                <langName/>
                <content>, the negative temporal idea of  'no when' is expressed by one or more verbal affixes, rather than by separate words.  Examples of the affix(es) attached to verbs include:</content>
            </p>
            <example show="swAdvPNegTemporalTypeAffix">
                <interlinear exampleLoc="advp/negTemporalAffixExample"/>
            </example>
            <p show="swAdvPNegTemporalTypeVerb">
                <content>In </content>
                <langName/>
                <content>, there is only a verbal negative affix, but it may occur with positive temporal adverbs to give a negative temporal meaning.  Examples of temporal adverbs with a negative verb include:</content>
            </p>
            <p show="swAdvPNegTemporalTypeWord">
                <content>In </content>
                <langName/>
                <content>, the negative temporal idea of  'no when' is expressed by one or more separate words.  Examples include:</content>
            </p>
            <example show="swAdvPNegTemporalTypeWordOrVerb">
                <interlinear exampleLoc="advp/negTemporalExample"/>
            </example>
            <p>
                <content>See section </content>
                <sectionRef sec="sNegAdverb"/>
                <content> for full sentence examples of the negative temporal expressions.</content>
            </p>
            <p>
                <content>The time element of a sentence can also be expressed by other types of words or phrases, such as: nominal phrases </content>
                <langData>yesterday</langData>
                <content>,
</content>
                <langData>last night</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>next year</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>tomorrow</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>a long time ago</langData>
                <content>; prepositional
phrases </content>
                <langData>for a long time</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>in a little while</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>at 10 o'clock</langData>
                <content>; and
adverbial clauses </content>
                <langData>while you are working</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>when Sue arrived</langData>
                <content>.  These phrases occur in the same positions as the temporal adverbs, normally either initially or finally in the clause.  See section </content>
                <sectionRef sec="sNP"/>
                <content> for the structure of nominal phrases and section </content>
                <sectionRef sec="sPP"/>
                <content> for information on </content><case element="pp" attr="pPos">
                    <caseText value="before">prepositional</caseText>
                    <caseText value="after">postpositional</caseText>
                    <caseText value="before">prepositional and postpositional</caseText>
                    <caseText value="unknown">prepositional and/or postpositional</caseText>
                </case><content> phrases.  See also section </content>
                <sectionRef sec="sAdvClTemporal"/>
                <content> for examples of temporal adverbial clauses.</content>
            </p>
        </section2>
        <section2 id="sAdvPLocative">
            <secTitle>Locative Adverbs</secTitle>
            <p>
                <content>Locative adverbs include the English words: </content>
                <langData>here</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>there</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>everywhere</langData>
                <content>.  Locative adverbs can be modified by </content>
                <langData>only</langData>
                <content> and </content>
                <langData>right</langData>
                <content>, as in: </content>
                <langData>only here</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>right here</langData>
                <content> and </content>
                <langData>right there</langData>
                <content>.  Many languages also have a negative locative adverb meaning </content>
                <langData>nowhere</langData>
                <content>.</content>
            </p>
            <p>
                <content>Examples of </content>
                <langName/>
                <content> positive locative adverbs and any degree words which can modify them include:
</content>
            </p>
            <example>
                <interlinear exampleLoc="advp/locativeExample"/>
            </example>
            <p show="swAdvPNegLocativeTypeAffix">
                <content>In </content>
                <langName/>
                <content>, the negative locative idea of  'nowhere' is expressed by one or more verbal affixes, rather than by separate words.  Examples of the affix(es) attached to verbs include:</content>
            </p>
            <example show="swAdvPNegLocativeTypeAffix">
                <interlinear exampleLoc="advp/negLocativeAffixExample"/>
            </example>
             <p show="swAdvPNegLocativeTypeVerb">
                <content>In </content>
                <langName/>
                <content>, there is only a verbal negative affix, but it may occur with positive locative adverbs to give a negative locative meaning.  Examples of locative adverbs with a negative verb include:</content>
            </p>
           <p show="swAdvPNegLocativeTypeWord">
                <content>In </content>
                <langName/>
                <content>, the negative locative idea of  'nowhere' is expressed by one or more separate words.  Examples include:</content>
            </p>
            <example show="swAdvPNegLocativeTypeWordOrVerb">
                <interlinear exampleLoc="advp/negLocativeExample"/>
            </example>
            <p>
                <content>See section </content>
                <sectionRef sec="sNegAdverb"/>
                <content> for full sentence examples of the negative locative expressions.</content>
            </p>
            <p>
                <content>Location is often also expressed by a prepositional
phrase, such as: </content>
                <langData>in the mountains</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>at San Jose</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>over there</langData>
                <content>.  Many
languages allow just a nominal phrase, consisting of a proper noun or
description of the place.  Locative expressions may normally occur either initially or finally in the clause, or as complements to motion verbs.  See section </content>
                <sectionRef sec="sIPMotion"/>
                <content> for examples with motion verbs.
</content>
            </p>
        </section2>
        <section2 id="sAdvPManner">
            <secTitle>Manner Adverbs</secTitle>
            <p>
                <content>Manner adverbs directly modify the verb and usually end in </content>
                <langData>-ly</langData>
                <content> in English.  These
manner adverbs can be modified by </content>
                <langData>very</langData>
                <content>
and </content>
                <langData>so</langData>
                <content>, as in: </content>
                <langData>very quickly</langData>
                <content>, </content>
                <langData>so slowly</langData>
                <content> and </content>
                <langData>very well</langData>
                <content>.</content>
            </p>
            <p>
                <content>Examples of </content>
                <langName/>
                <content> manner adverbs and any degree words which can modify them include:
</content>
            </p>
            <example>
                <interlinear exampleLoc="advp/mannerExample"/>
            </example>
            <p show="swAdvPMannerTypeAffix">
                <content>Manner adverbs in </content>
                <langName/>
                <content> are all written as affixes on the verb, rather than being separate words.</content>
            </p>
        </section2>
        <section2 id="sAdvPReason">
            <secTitle>Reason or Purpose Adverbs</secTitle>
            <p>
                <content>Reason or purpose adverbs include </content>
                <langData>therefore</langData>
                <content> and
</content>
                <langData>so</langData>
                <content>.  Reason or purpose adverbs do not allow modifiers in English.  Reason or purpose can also be expressed by an adverbial clause beginning with </content>
                <langData>because</langData>
                <content> or </content>
                <langData>since</langData>
                <content> or </content>
                <langData>in order</langData>
                <content>.  These adverbial phrases or clauses occur either initially or finally in the sentence.</content>
            </p>
            <p>
                <content>Examples of </content>
                <langName/>
                <content> reason or purpose adverbs or adverbial clauses, included in full sentences are:
</content>
            </p>
            <example>
                <interlinear exampleLoc="advp/reasonExample"/>
            </example>
            <p>
                <content>The structure of the adverbial clauses will be addressed in section </content>
                <sectionRef sec="sAdvClReason"/>
                <content>.  Reason or purpose can also be expressed by a prepositional phrase, such as </content>
                <langData>for this reason</langData>
                <content> or </content>
                <langData>on purpose</langData>
                <content>.  Such phrases are described in section </content>
                <sectionRef sec="sPP"/>
                <content>.
</content>
            </p>
        </section2>
    </section1>
